Colloquially, the phrase "genetic makeup" is sometimes used to denote the genome of a particular individual or organism. context_en: Antibacterial antibiotics are usually classified based on their mechanism of action, chemical structure, or spectrum of activity. Most target bacterial functions or growth processes. Those that target the bacterial cell wall (penicillins and cephalosporins) or cell membrane (polymyxins), or interfere with essential bacterial enzymes (rifamicins, lipiromycins, quinolones, and sulfonamides) have bactericidal activities. Those that target protein synthesis (macrolides, lincosamides, and tetracyclines) are generally bacteriostatic (with the exception of bactericidal aminoglycosides). Further classification is based on their target specificity. "Narrow spectrum" antibacterial antibiotics target specific types of bacteria, such as gram-negative or gram-positive bacteria, while broad spectrum antibiotics affect a wide range of bacteria. After a 40-year hiatus in the discovery of new classes of antibacterial compounds, four new classes of antibacterial antibiotics have been brought into clinical use in the late 2000s and early 2010s: cyclic lipopeptides (e.g. daptomycin), glycylcholines. (such as tigecycline), oxazolidinones (such as linezolid), and liparimycin (such as fidaxomicin).
questions_en: How many new classes of antibacterial antibiotics were introduced in the late 2000s?

context_en: The inherent ambiguity of many control characters, combined with their historical usage, created problems when transferring "plain text" files between systems. The best example of this is the new problem on different operating systems. Teletype machines require that a line of text be processed by both a "carriage return" (which moves the printhead to the beginning of the line) and a "line feed" (which advances the paper one line without printing). The name "carriage return" comes from the fact that the carriage holding the paper on a manual typewriter was moved, where that type of bamboo held the ribbon stationary. The entire carriage had to be pushed to the right (returned) to position the left margin of the paper for the next line.
questions_en: Why were problems created when transferring files between systems?

context_en: In physics, Whitehead's ideas have had some influence. He expressed a view that might perhaps be considered a form of Einstein's general relativity, see Whitehead's theory of gravitation. This has been seriously criticized. Yutaka Tanaka, who suggests that the gravitational constant disagrees with experimental findings, proposes that Einstein's work does not actually refute Whitehead's formulation. Whitehead's view has now been rendered obsolete with the discovery of gravitational waves. Those phenomena have been observed locally that violate the local flatness of large-scale space that Whitehead assumes. As a result, Whitehead's universe should be treated as a local conjecture, and his notion of a similar spatio-temporal geometry, the Minkoloskian, should often be treated as a locally-sufficient conjecture. An accurate replacement of Whitehead's cosmology would require accepting Riemannian geometry. Furthermore, although Whitehead himself gave only secondary consideration to quantum theory, the metaphysics of processes has proven attractive to some physicists in that field. Henry Stapp and David Boehm are among those whose work has been influenced by Whitehead.

Ethnography can refer to both a methodology and the product of ethnographic research, i. An ethnographic monograph. As a methodology, ethnography is based on long-term fieldwork within a community or other research site. Participant observation is one of the foundational methods of social and cultural anthropology. Ethnography involves the systematic comparison of different cultures. The process of participant-observation can be especially helpful in understanding culture from an emic (ideological, VS) perspective. etic, or technical) approach.

context_en: The island covers an area of ​​25 square kilometers (2,500 ha). The eastern side is wetter than the western. Although the climate is essentially dry, rainfall averages 1000 mm annually, but with considerable variation across terrain. Summer is from May to November, which is also the rainy season. Winter is the dry season from December to April. Sunshine is very prominent almost all year round and also during the rainy season. Humidity, however, is not very high due to the winds. The average temperature is around 25 °C with daytime highs rising up to 32 °C. The average high and low temperatures in January are 28 °C and 22 °C respectively, while in July they are 30 °C and 24 °C. The lowest night temperature recorded is 13 °C. The Caribbean sea water in the surrounding area usually maintains a temperature of around 27 °C.

context_en: Portugal's rapid economic growth in the early 1970s set a priority for improving transportation with increased consumption and purchases of new automobiles. context_en: Feynman devoted the latter half of his book to what you know about what other people think. Rogers deviates from his usual convention of brief, light-hearted anecdotes to deliver an extended and sober narrative of his experience on the commission. Feynman's account reveals a disconnect between NASA engineers and officials that was far more striking than might have been expected. His interviews of high-ranking NASA managers revealed shocking misunderstandings of elementary concepts. For example, NASA managers claimed there was a 1 in 100,000 chance of a catastrophic failure aboard the shuttle, but Feynman found that NASA's own engineers had estimated the chance of a disaster closer to 1 in 200. He concluded that NASA management's estimates of space shuttle reliability were shockingly unrealistic, and he was particularly angered that NASA used these figures to recruit Christy McAuliffe into the Teacher-in-Space program. He warned in its appendix to the Commission's report (which was included only after he threatened to sign the report, "for a successful technique"), reality must take priority over public relations, nature must not be fooled. context_en: When u. entered World War II on December 8, 1941, many Montanans had already enlisted in the military to escape the poor national economy of the previous decade. Another 40,000 Montanans entered the armed forces in the first year after the declaration of war, and more than 57,000 joined before the war ended. These numbers constituted approximately 10 percent of the state's total population, and Montana again contributed one of the highest numbers of soldiers per capita of any state. Many Native Americans were among those who joined the troops, including soldiers from the Crow Nation who became code talkers. At least 1,500 Montanans died in the battle. Montana was also the training site for the first Special Service Force or "Devil Brigade", a joint U.S. S-Canadian commando-style force that trains at Fort William Henry Harrison for experience in mountainous and winter conditions prior to deployment. Air bases were built at Great Falls, Lewistown, Cut Bank, and Glasgow, some of which were used as staging areas to prepare aircraft to be sent to Allied forces in the Soviet Union. During the war, approximately 30 Japanese balloon bombs were documented to have landed in Montana, although no casualties nor major wildfires were attributed to them.

context_en: Richard Phillips Feynman (/ˈfaɪnmən/; May 11, 1918 – February 15, 1988) was an American theoretical physicist best known for his work in the path integral formulation of quantum mechanics, the theory of quantum electrodynamics, and the physics of supercooled superfluidity. In 1835 Chopin went to Carlsbad, where he spent time with his parents; the last time he would see them. On his way back to Paris, he met old friends from Warsaw, the Wodzińskis. He introduced his daughter Maria to Poland five years ago, when she was eleven. This meeting led him to stay for two weeks in Dresden, when he had previously intended to return to Paris via Leipzig. The composer's portrait of a sixteen-year-old girl, along with Delacroix's, are regarded as Chopin's best parallels. In October he finally reached Leipzig, where he met Schumann, Clara Wieck and Felix Mendelssohn, who performed for him his own oratorio St. Paul, and who considered him "an ideal musician". In July 1836 Chopin traveled with the Wodziński family to Marienbad and Dresden, and in September he proposed to Maria, whose mother Countess Wodzińska approved in principle. Chopin moved to Leipzig, where he presented Schumann with his G minor Ballade. At the end of 1836 he sent Maria an album in which her sister Ludwika had inscribed seven of his songs, and his 1835 Nocturne in C-sharp minor, Op. 27, no. context_en: Antibacterial antibiotics are usually classified based on their mechanism of action, chemical structure, or spectrum of activity. Most target bacterial functions or growth processes. Those that target the bacterial cell wall (penicillins and cephalosporins) or cell membrane (polymyxins), or interfere with essential bacterial enzymes (rifamicins, lipiromycins, quinolones, and sulfonamides) have bactericidal activities. Those that target protein synthesis (macrolides, lincosamides, and tetracyclines) are generally bacteriostatic (with the exception of bactericidal aminoglycosides). Further classification is based on their target specificity. "Narrow spectrum" antibacterial antibiotics target specific types of bacteria, such as gram-negative or gram-positive bacteria, while broad spectrum antibiotics affect a wide range of bacteria. After a 40-year hiatus in the discovery of new classes of antibacterial compounds, four new classes of antibacterial antibiotics have been brought into clinical use in the late 2000s and early 2010s: cyclic lipopeptides (e.g. daptomycin), glycylcholines. (such as tigecycline), oxazolidinones (such as linezolid), and liparimycin (such as fidaxomicin).
questions_en: What do antibiotics mostly target?

He has maintained worldwide renown as one of the leading composers of his era and "poetic genius was based on a professional technique that had no equal in his generation." Chopin was born in the Duchy of Warsaw, and grew up in Warsaw. , which became part of Congress Poland after 1815. context_en: In 1977, Gaddafi dissolved the republic and created a new socialist state, the Jamahiriya ("people's state"). Gaddafi's support for foreign terrorists, overseeing unsuccessful border conflicts with Egypt and Chad, and alleged responsibility for the Lockerbie bombing led to Libya's label of "international pariah". A particularly hostile relationship developed with the United States and the United Kingdom, resulting in the 1986 U.N. The bombing of Libya and UN-imposed economic sanctions. Rejecting his previous ideological commitments, from 1999 onwards Gaddafi encouraged economic privatization and sought rapprochement with Western countries, while also embracing Pan-Africanism and helping to establish the African Union. Amid the Arab Spring, an anti-Gadda rebellion led by the National Transitional Council (NTC) broke out in 2011, resulting in the Libyan Civil War. NATO intervened militarily in favor of the NTC, bringing about the fall of the government. Retreating to Sirte, Gaddafi was captured and executed by NTC militants.

context_en: Evolutionary anthropology is the interdisciplinary study of the evolution of human physiology and human behavior and the relationship between hominins and non-hominin primates. It is based on a scientific approach, and brings together fields such as archaeology, behavioral ecology, psychology, primatology, and genetics. It is a dynamic and interdisciplinary field, drawing on multiple lines of evidence to understand the human experience, past and present.

context_en: In higher organisms (like people), these two modes of perception combine in what Whitehead terms "symbolic reference", linking appearance with reason in a process that is so automatic that both people and animals are able to avoid it. There is difficulty. By way of illustration, Whitehead uses the example of a person's encounter with a chair. An ordinary person looks up, sees a colorful shape, and immediately assumes it is a chair. However, an artist, Whitehead believes, "might not jump to the notion of a chair", but instead might stop at "the mere contemplation of a beautiful color and the contemplation of a beautiful shape." There is no reaction; Most people place objects into categories by habit and instinct, without even thinking about it. Besides, animals do the same thing. Using the same example, Whitehead explains that a dog "will act immediately on the hypothesis of a chair and thus will have jumped through to use it." Thus symbolic reference is a fusion of pure emotion perceptions on the one hand and On the other side are causal relations, and it is precisely the causal relations that dominate the more basic mentality (as the dog shows), while it is the sense perceptions that point to a higher grade mentality (as the artist shows).

context_en: Since life began on Earth, five major mass extinctions and several minor events have led to large and sudden drops in biodiversity. The Phanerozoic Eon (the last 540 million years) saw a rapid increase in biodiversity through the Cambrian explosion – a period during which the majority of paleontology first appeared. Repeated over the next 400 million years, massive biodiversity losses classified as mass extinction events occurred. In Carbonfarmer, rainforest collapse caused a major loss of plant and animal life. The worst was the Permian–Triassic extinction event 251 million years ago; vertebrate recovery took 30 million years. The most recent, the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, occurred 65 million years ago and often receives more attention than others because it resulted in the extinction of the dinosaurs.

context_en: Sociological anthropology draws together the principle strands of cultural anthropology and social anthropology. Cultural anthropology is more concerned with philosophy, literature, and the arts (how one's culture influences experience for the self and group, contributing to a more complete understanding of people's knowledge, customs, and institutions), while social anthropology More related to sociology and history. In this it helps develop an understanding of social structures, usually between others and other populations (e.g. minorities, subgroups, dissidents, etc.) There is no hard and fast distinction between them, and these categories overlap to a great extent.

context_en: Montana is home to a diverse array of fauna including 14 amphibians, 90 fish, 117 mammals, 20 reptiles and 427 bird species. context_en: Several molecular mechanisms of antibacterial resistance exist. Intrinsic antibacterial resistance may be part of the genetic makeup of bacterial strains. For example, an antibiotic target may be absent from the bacterial genome. Acquired resistance results from a mutation in the bacterial chromosome or the acquisition of extra chromosomal DNA. Antibacterial-producing bacteria have evolved resistance mechanisms that have been shown to be similar, and have been transferred to antibacterial-resistant strains. The spread of antibacterial resistance often occurs through vertical transmission of mutations during evolution and by genetic recombination of DNA by horizontal genetic exchange. For example, antibacterial resistance genes can be exchanged through these resistance genes between different bacterial strains or species. Plasmids that carry several different resistance genes can confer multiple antibacterial resistance. Cross-resistance to multiple antibacterials can also occur when a resistance mechanism encoded by a single gene confers resistance to more than one antibacterial compound.
questions_en: What is part of the makeup of bacterial strains?

context_en: Mahayana Buddhism received important theoretical grounding from Nagarjuna (probably c. 150–250 CE), arguably the most influential scholar within the Mahayana tradition. Nāgārjuna's primary contribution to Buddhist philosophy was the systematic exposition of the concept of śśnyatā, or "emptiness", which was widely attested in the Prajñapāmita sutras that emerged in his era. The concept of emptiness brings together a rejection of other major Buddhist doctrines, particularly anatta and dependent origination, the metaphysics of Sarvottvāda and Sautrantika (extinct non-Mahayana school). For Nāgārjuna, it is not only sentient beings that are empty of āman; all phenomena (dharma) are without any sentient (literally "self-nature" or "self-nature"), and thus without any inherent of essence; they are "empty" of independent being; thus the heterodox doctrines of the self circulating in time were rejected based on the principles of early Buddhism. Nagarjuna's school of thought is known as Dadhamaka. Some writings attributed to Nāgārjuna made explicit references to Mahayana texts, but argued his philosophy within the parameters set by the Agamas. He may have arrived at his positions from a desire to achieve a consistent exegesis of the Buddha's doctrine as recorded in the canon. In Nagarjuna's view the Buddha was not merely a precursor but the founder of the Madhyayaka system.
questions_en: What is the meaning of Sanyata?

context_en: From September 1823 to 1826 Chopin attended the Warsaw Lyceum, where he received organ lessons from the Czech composer Wilhelm Wurfel during his first year. In the autumn of 1826 he began a three-year course under the Silesian composer Józef Elsner at the Warsaw Conservatory, studying music theory, bass and composition. [n3] During this period he continued to write and to give recitals in concerts and salons in Warsaw. He was engaged by the inventors of a mechanical organ, the "Eolomelodikon", and in May 1825 on this instrument he performed his own improvisations and part of a concerto by Moscheles. The success of this concert led to an invitation from Tsar Alexander I, who was visiting Warsaw, to perform a similar citation on the first instrument; the tsar presented him with a diamond ring. At the subsequent Éolomelodikon concert on 10 June 1825, Chopin performed his Rondo Op. It was the first of his works to be published commercially and earned him his first mention in the foreign press, when the Leipzig Allgemeine Musikalische Zeitung praised its "wealth of musical ideas".

context_en: In late 1831, Chopin received his first major endorsement from an outstanding contemporary when Robert Schumann, reviewing Op. 2 Variations in the Allgemeine Musikalische Zeitung (his first published article on music), declared: "Salute, gentlemen! A genius." On 26 February 1832 Chopin gave a Paris concert at the Salle Paris to universal praise. The critic François-Joseph Fétis wrote in the Revue et Gazette Musicale: "Here is a young man. Taking no models, he has found, if not a complete renewal of piano music, an abundance of original ideas of a kind not found anywhere else. "After this concert, Chopin realized that his essentially intimate keyboard technique was not optimal for larger concert spaces. Later that year she was introduced to the wealthy Rothschild banking family, whose patronage also opened the doors for her to other private salons (aristocracy and social gatherings of the artistic and literary elite). By the end of 1832 Chopin had established himself among the musical elite of Paris, and had earned the respect of his peers such as Hill, Liszt, and Berlioz. He was no longer financially dependent on his father, and in the winter of 1832 he began to earn a handsome income from publishing his works and teaching piano to wealthy students throughout Europe. This freed him from the strains of public concerts, which he disliked.

context_en: Before the 20th century, the term matter included ordinary matter composed of atoms and excluded other energy phenomena such as light or sound. This concept of matter can be generalized from atoms to include any object that has mass even when at rest, but it is ill-defined because the mass of an object depends on the motion of its (presumably massive) components. And interactions can arise from energy. Thus, matter does not have a universal definition, nor is it a fundamental concept in physics today. Matter is also used as a general term for the substance that makes up all observable physical objects.
questions_en: What term is used for the substance that makes up all observable physical objects?

context_en: The successful outcome of antimicrobial therapy with antibacterial compounds depends on many factors. These include host defense mechanisms, site of infection, and the biochemical and pharmacodynamic properties of the antibacterial. The bactericidal activity of antibacterials may depend on the bacterial growth stage, and it often requires ongoing metabolic activity and division of bacterial cells. These findings are based on laboratory studies, and have also been shown to eliminate bacterial infections in clinical settings. Since the activity of an antibacterial often depends on its concentration, in vitro characterization of antibacterial activity usually involves determining the minimum inhibitory concentration and the minimum bactericidal concentration of an antibacterial. To predict clinical outcome, the antimicrobial activity of an antibacterial is usually combined with its Pharmacokinetic profile, and several pharmacological parameters are used as markers of drug efficacy.

context_en: South Korea: The event was held in Seoul, which hosted the 1988 Summer Olympics, on 27 April. Intended torchbearers Choi Seung-kuk and Park Won-sun boycotted the event in protest of the Chinese government's crackdown on Tibet. More than 8,000 riot police were deployed to guard the 24-kilometre route, which began at the Olympic Park, where Seoul hosted the 1988 Summer Games. On the day of the torch relay in Seoul, Chinese students clashed with protesters, throwing rocks, bottles and screws. A North Korean defector whose brother defected to China but was captured and executed by the DPRK attempted to set himself on fire in protest against China's treatment of North Korean refugees. He poured gasoline on himself but police quickly surrounded him and took him away. Two other protesters tried to storm the torch but failed. Fighting broke out near the start of the relay between a group of 500 Chinese supporters and about 50 protesters who carried a banner that read: "Free North Korean refugees in China." Students threw stones and water bottles as about 2,500 police. Tried to keep the groups separate. Police said they arrested five people, including a Chinese student who was arrested for allegedly throwing rocks. Thousands of Chinese followed the torch on their own. A 5-hour journey, with some chanting, "Go China, go Olympics!" By the end of the relay, the Chinese students turned violent, and it was reported in the Korean media that they were "lynching" anyone who disagreed with them. . A police man was taken to hospital after being attacked by Chinese students. On April 29, Justice Secretary Kim Kyung Han told the Prime Minister that he would find "every single Chinese who was involved and bring them to justice." Later, South Korea's Prosecutor's Office, the National Police Agency, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and The Ministry of National Intelligence said in a joint statement that they would deport every Chinese student involved in the incident. China defended the students' conduct.

context_en: Genocide has become an official term in international relations. Genocide was not used before 1944. Earlier, in 1941, Winston Churchill described the mass murder of Russian prisoners of war and civilians as "a crime without a crime". That year, a Polish-Jewish lawyer named Raphael Lemkin described the policies of systematic murder instituted by the Nazis as genocide. The word genocide is a combination of the Greek prefix xeno- (meaning tribe or race) and cadre (the Latin word for killing). The term is defined as a specific set of violent crimes that are committed against a certain group with an attempt to remove the entire group from existence or destroy them.

context_en: Germany has a comprehensive school known as Gesamtschule. In most cases students attending a Gesamtschule can graduate with a Hauptschulaschluss, Realschulabschluss or Abitur depending on how well they performed in school.

context_en: Westminster Abbey, formally the Collegiate Church of St Peter at Westminster, is a large, mainly Gothic abbey church in the City of Westminster, London, located to the west of the Palace of Westminster. It is one of the most notable religious buildings in the United Kingdom and has been the traditional location of coronation and burial site for English and, later, British monarchs. Between 1540 and 1556 the abbey had the status of a cathedral. Since 1560, the building is no longer an abbey nor a cathedral, instead having the status of a Church of England "Royal Peculiar"—a church directly responsible to the sovereign. The building itself is the original abbey church.

context_en: On the other hand, the change through the Phanerozoic fits much better with hyperbolic models (widely used in population biology, demography and macrosociology, as well as fossil biodiversity) than with exponential and logistic models. The latter model implies that changes in diversity are guided by first order positive feedback (more ancestors, more descendants) and/or negative feedback resulting from resource limitation. The hyperbolic model implies a second-order positive feedback. The hyperbolic pattern of world population growth arises from a second-order positive feedback between population size and the rate of technological progress. The hyperbolic character of biodiversity growth can be equated to the feedback between diversity and community structure complexity. The similarity between biodiversity and human population curves probably comes from the fact that both are derived from the interference of hyperbolic trend with cyclical and stochastic dynamics.

context_en: Exposure to antibiotics early in life increases body mass in humans and mouse models. Early life is a critical period for the establishment of the intestinal microbiota and metabolic development. Mice exposed to the above antibiotic treatments (STAT) – either penicillin, vancomycin, penicillin and vancomycin, or chlortetracycline had altered composition of the gut microbiota as well as its metabolic capabilities. Additionally, research has shown that rats given low dose penicillin (1 μg/g body weight) around birth and throughout the lactation process had decreased body mass and fat mass, accelerated growth, and hepatic expression of genes involved in adipogenesis. Expression was increased in control rats. Furthermore, penicillin in combination with a high-fat diet rapidly increased insulin levels in rats. However, it is unclear whether antibiotics cause obesity in humans. Studies have found a correlation between early exposure to antibiotics (<6 months) and increased body mass (at 10 and 20 months). Another study found that the type of antibiotic exposure was also important, with those macrolides having the highest risk of overweight compared to penicillins and cephalosporins. Therefore, there is an association between antibiotic exposure in early life and obesity in humans, but whether there is a causal relationship is unclear. Although there is a correlation between antibiotic use in early life and obesity, the effect of antibiotics on obesity in humans must weigh against the beneficial effects of clinically indicated treatment with antibiotics in childhood.

context_en: This credit freeze brought the global financial system to the brink of collapse. The response of the Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank, the Bank of England, and other central banks was immediate and dramatic. During the last quarter of 2008, these central banks purchased US$2.5 trillion of government debt and troubled private assets from banks. It was the largest liquidity injection into the credit markets, and the largest monetary policy action in world history. Following a model initiated by the United Kingdom bank rescue package, the governments of European countries and the United States guaranteed the debt issued by their banks and raised the capital of their national banking systems, ultimately injecting $1.5 trillion of new money into their major banks. Purchased issued preferred stock. In October 2010, Nobel laureate Joseph Stiglitz described how the U.S. The Federal Reserve was implementing another monetary policy – ​​currency creation – as a method to deal with the liquidity trap. By creating $600 billion and [clarification needed] putting it directly into banks, the Federal Reserve intended to induce banks to finance more home loans and refinance mortgages. However, banks were instead spending money in more profitable areas by investing internationally in emerging markets. Banks were also investing in foreign currencies, which Stiglitz and others point out could lead to currency wars while China redirects its currency holdings away from the United States.

context_en: Muammar Gaddafi was born in a tent near Qasr Abu Hadi, a rural area outside the city of Sirte in the western Libyan desert. His father Mohammed Abdul Salam bin Hamed bin Mohammed was known as Abu Menyar (died 1985), and his mother was named Aisha (died 1978); Abu Menyar was a goat and camel herder. Earned a meager subsistence as. Nomadic Bedouins, they were illiterate and kept no birth records. Thus, Gaddafi's date of birth is not known with certainty, and sources have placed it in spring of 1942 or 1943, although biographers Blundy and Lycett note that it may be as early as 1940. The only surviving son of his parents, he had three elder sisters. Gaddafi's upbringing in Bedouin culture influenced his personal tastes for the rest of his life. context_en: France: The torch relay leg in Paris, held on 7 April, started on the first level of the Eiffel Tower and finished at the Stade Charliet. A scheduled ceremony at the town hall was cancelled, and at the request of Chinese officials, the torch ended the relay by bus rather than being carried by the athletes. Paris city officials had announced plans to greet the Olympic flame with a peaceful protest when the torch was to reach the French capital. Members of Journalists Without Borders joined the mass protest. Came out for. context_en: Digestion begins in the mouth with the secretion of saliva and its digestive enzymes. Gastric juice contains hydrochloric acid and pepsin which will damage the stomach walls and the mucus secreted for protection. The release of enzymes in the stomach breaks down the food further and this is combined with the churning action of the stomach. Partially digested food enters the duodenum as a thick semi-liquid chyme. In the small intestine, the majority of digestion takes place and is facilitated by secretions of bile, pancreatic juice, and intestinal juice. The intestinal walls are lined with villi, and their epithelial cells are covered with numerous microvilli to improve the absorption of nutrients by increasing the surface area of ​​the intestine.

As early as 1837, Maria Wodzińska's mother had made it clear to Chopin in correspondence that the marriage with her daughter was unlikely to proceed. It is believed that she was influenced by his poor health and possibly also by rumors about him having affairs with men and women like Sand. Chopin eventually placed the letters from Maria and her mother in a package on which he wrote, in Polish, "My Tragedy". Sand, in a letter to Grzymała of June 1838, acknowledged strong feelings for the composer and argued for leaving the current relationship to begin an affair with Chopin; he asked Grzymała to assess Chopin's relationship with Maria Wodzińska. Without realizing that the matter, at least from Maria's side, was over.

context_en: The island covers an area of ​​25 square kilometers (2,500 ha). The eastern side is wetter than the western. Although the climate is essentially dry, rainfall averages 1000 mm annually, but with considerable variation across terrain. Summer is from May to November, which is also the rainy season. Winter is the dry season from December to April. Sunshine is very prominent almost all year round and also during the rainy season. Humidity, however, is not very high due to the winds. The average temperature is around 25 °C with daytime highs rising up to 32 °C. The average high and low temperatures in January are 28 °C and 22 °C respectively, while in July they are 30 °C and 24 °C. The lowest night temperature recorded is 13 °C. The Caribbean sea water in the surrounding area usually maintains a temperature of around 27 °C.

context_en: Global agreements, such as the Convention on Biological Diversity, give "sovereign national rights" (not property) to biological resources. The agreement commits countries to "conserve biodiversity", "develop resources for sustainability" and "share the benefits" from their use. Biodiverse countries that allow bioprospecting or collection of natural products expect a share of the benefits rather than allowing the individual or entity that discovers/exploits the resource to capture them privately. Bioprospecting can become a type of biopiracy when such principles are not respected. [citation needed].
questions_en: Does the agreement commit countries to develop resources for sustainability?

context_en: In 2004, the Swaziland government acknowledged for the first time that it faced an AIDS crisis, with 38. 8% of pregnant women tested became infected with HIV (see AIDS in Africa). Then-Prime Minister Theba Dlamini declared a humanitarian crisis due to the combined effects of drought, land degradation, increased poverty, and HIV/AIDS. According to a 2011 UNAIDS report, Swaziland is close to achieving universal access to HIV/AIDS treatment, defined as 80% coverage or more. Estimates of treatment coverage range from 70% to 80% of those infected. Life expectancy had fallen from 61 years in 2000 to 32 years in 2000. Tuberculosis is also a significant problem with an 18% mortality rate. Many patients have a multi-drug resistant strain, and 83% are co-infected with HIV.
questions_en: Why does UNAIDS consider universal access to HIV/AIDS treatment?

context_en: Biodiversity, a contraction of "biological diversity", generally refers to the diversity and variability of life on Earth. One of the most widely used definitions defines it in terms of variability within species, between species, and between ecosystems. It is a measure of the diversity of organisms present in different ecosystems. It may refer to genetic variation, ecosystem variation, or species variation (number of species) within a region, biome, or planet. Terrestrial biodiversity tends to be greater near the equator, which appears to be a result of the warmer climate and higher primary productivity. Biodiversity is not distributed evenly on Earth. It is the richest in the tropics. Marine biodiversity is highest along the coasts in the western Pacific, where sea surface temperatures are highest and in mid-latitude bands of all oceans. There are latitudinal gradients in species diversity. Biodiversity is generally clustered in hotspots, and has been increasing through time, but will likely slow in the future.
questions_en: What term refers to the diversity and variability of life on Earth?

context_en: This credit freeze brought the global financial system to the brink of collapse. Purchased issued preferred stock. In October 2010, Nobel laureate Joseph Stiglitz described how the U.S. The Federal Reserve was implementing another monetary policy – ​​currency creation – as a method to deal with the liquidity trap. By creating $600 billion and [clarification needed] putting it directly into banks, the Federal Reserve intended to induce banks to finance more home loans and refinance mortgages. However, banks were instead spending money in more profitable areas by investing internationally in emerging markets. Banks were also investing in foreign currencies, which Stiglitz and others point out could lead to currency wars while China redirects its currency holdings away from the United States.

context_en: Sociologist James A. Beckford, in a 1975 study of Jehovah's Witnesses, classified the religion's organizational structure as characterized by an assertive leadership, specific and narrow objectives, competing demands on members' time and energy, and control over the quality of new members. Control. Other characteristics of the classification include the potential for friction with secular authorities, reluctance to co-operate with other religious organizations, high rates of membership turnover, low rates of doctrinal change, and strict uniformity of beliefs among members. Beckford identified the religion's main characteristics as historicism (recognizing historical events as historical events), absolutism (the strong belief that Jehovah's Witnesses leave the complete truth to leaders), activism (members are encouraged to engage in missionary activities, the ability to motivate members to act), rationalism (the conviction that Witness doctrines have a rational basis over mystical ones), authoritarianism (rigid presentation of rules without opportunity for criticism) and world indifference (satisfaction with certain secular needs and medical Refuse treatments).

context_en: The digestive system of an earthworm consists of a mouth, pharynx, esophagus, crop, gizzard, and intestine. The mouth is surrounded by strong lips, which act like hands to grasp pieces of dead grass, leaves and weeds, helping to chew along bits of soil. Lips break food into smaller pieces. In the pharynx, food is lubricated by mucous secretions for easy passage. The esophagus adds calcium carbonate to neutralize the acid formed by decaying foods. The crop consists of temporary storage where food and calcium carbonate are mixed. The powerful muscles of the gizzard churn and mix the mass of food and dirt. When churning is complete, glands in the walls of the gizzard add enzymes to the thick paste, which helps chemically break down the organic matter. By peristalsis, the mixture is sent to the intestine where friendly bacteria continue the chemical breakdown. It releases carbohydrates, proteins, fats, and various vitamins and minerals for absorption into the body.
questions_en: What does an earthworm's digestive system include?
answers_en: A mouth, pharynx, esophagus, crop, gizzard, and intestine

context_en: The two became friends, and for several years lived in Paris, Chopin at 38 Rue de la Chaussee-d'Antin, and Liszt at the Hotel de France on Rue Lafitte, a few blocks away. They performed together on seven occasions between 1833 and 1841. The first, on 2 April 1833, was at a benefit concert conducted by Hector Berlioz for his bankrupt Shakespearean actress wife Harriet Smithson, during which he played George Onslow's Sonata in F minor for piano duet. Later joint appearances included a benefit concert for the Polish Women's Benevolent Association in Paris. His last appearance in public was for a charity concert organized for the Beethoven memorial in Bonn, held at the Salle Pöltl and the Paris Conservatory on 25 and 26 April 1841.

In contrast, archeology and biological anthropology were largely positive. Because of this difference in epistemology, the four subfields of anthropology have lacked cohesion over the past several decades.

context_en: Approximately 66,000 people of Native American heritage live in Montana. Stemming from several treaties and federal legislation, including the Indian Regulation Act (1851), the Dawes Act (1887), and the Indian Reorganization Act (1934), seven Indian reservations, encompassing eleven tribal nations, were created in Montana. A twelfth nation, the Little Shell Chippewa, a "landless" people headquartered in Great Falls, is recognized by the state of Montana, but not by the U.S. Government. The headquarters of the Blackfeet Nation are at the Browning Indian Reservation (1851) at the Browning Agency, the Crow Indian Reservation (1851) at the Crow Agency, the Northern Indian Reservation (1855) at Pablo, the Flathead Indian Reservation (1855) at Pend d'Oreille, northern Cheyenne at the Cheyenne Indian Reservation (1884), Fort at the Belknap Agency (1888), Fort Supreme at the Indian Reservation (1888), Poplar at the Fort Peck Indian Reservation (1888), and Chippewa Parbox Elder's Cree on the nearby Rocky Boy Indian Reservation (1916). About 63% of all Native people live off reservations, concentrated in large Montana cities with the largest concentration of urban Indians in Great Falls. The state also has a small Métis population, and 1990 census data indicated that people from 275 different tribes lived in Montana.

context_en: Biodiversity provides important support for drug discovery and availability of medicinal resources. A significant proportion of drugs are derived directly or indirectly from biological sources: at least 50% of pharmaceutical compounds on the US market are derived from plants, animals, and micro-organisms, while approximately 80% of the world's population depends on primary health care. For medicines from nature (used in modern or traditional medical practice). Only a small fraction of wild species have been investigated for medical potential. Biodiversity has been important to advances in the entire field of bionics. Evidence from market analysis and biodiversity science suggests that the decline in production from the pharmaceutical sector since the mid-1980s can be attributed to the move away from natural product exploration ("bioprospecting") in favor of genomics and synthetic chemistry. , in fact claims about the value of undiscovered pharmaceuticals may not provide sufficient incentives for companies in free markets due to the high cost of developing them; meanwhile, natural products have a potential to support important economic and health innovation. Has a long history. context_en: In 1758, the taxonomist Linnaeus published a classification of species in Systema Naturae that included Canis species. Canis is a Latin word meaning dog, and the list includes dog-like carnivores: the domestic dog, wolves, foxes, and jackals. The dog was classified as Canis familiaris, meaning "dog-family" or family dog. On the next page he records the wolf as Canis lupus, meaning "dog-wolf". In 1978, a review aimed at reducing the number of recognized Canis species proposed that "Canis dingo is now generally regarded as a distinct feral domestic dog. Canis familiaris is used for domestic dogs. Although taxonomically it should probably be synonymous with Canis lupus." In 1982, the first edition of Mammal Species of the World listed Canis familiaris under Canis lupus with the comment: "Probably ancestral to the domestic dog. , Canis familiaris has priority over Canis lupus, but both were published together in Linnaeus (1758), and Canis lupus has been used universally for this species", which refers to the wolf as a member of the family. There was an avoidance of being classified as a dog. The dog is now listed as Canis lupus familiaris, among several other Latin-named subspecies of Canis lupus.
questions_en: What is the modern single English word for canis lupus?

context_en: The effects of certain types of mold on infection were observed several times throughout history (see: History of penicillin). Fleming said the effect is mediated by an antibacterial compound called penicillin, and its antibacterial properties could be exploited for chemotherapy. He initially characterized some of its biological properties, and attempted to use a crude preparation to treat some infections, but he was unable to pursue his further development without the assistance of trained chemists.

context_en: Jehovah's Witnesses believe that Jesus Christ began ruling in heaven as King of God's Kingdom in October 1914, and that Satan was then cast out of heaven to earth, resulting in "sorrow" for humanity. context_en: Nanjing has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen Cfa) and is under the influence of the East Asian monsoon. The four seasons are distinct, with moist conditions seen throughout the year, a very hot and muggy summer, a cold, moist winter, and a fair length of fall in the middle, spring and autumn. Along with Chongqing and Wuhan, Nanjing is traditionally known as one of the "Three Fernancial Cities" along the Yangtze River (长江流域三大火炉) for its perennially high temperatures in summer. However, mid-June to late July is the plum blossom blooming season marked by Meiyu (the rainy season of East Asia; literally "plum rain"), during which the city experiences a period of light rain in the form of humidity. Typhoons are uncommon but possible in the late stages of summer and early part of autumn. The annual average temperature is about 15. 46 °C (59.8 °F), with a monthly 24-hour average temperature ranging from 2. 4 °C (36.3° F) in January to 27.8 °C (82.0° F) in July. Extremes since 1951 have occurred at -14. 0 °C (7 °F) to 40 on 6 January 1955. 7 °C (105 °F) on 22 August 1959. The average rainfall is 115 days a year, and the average annual rainfall is 1,062 millimeters (42 in). With monthly percent possible sunshine ranging from 37 percent in March to 52 percent in August, the city receives 1,983 hours of bright sunshine annually.
questions_en: How many hours of bright sunshine does Nanjing get each year?

context_en: In 1836, at a party hosted by Marie d'Ault, Chopin met the French writer George Sand (born [Amantine] Aurore [Lucile] Dupin). Short (five feet, or 152 cm), dark, big-eyed, and a cigar smoker, she initially repulsed Chopin, who commented, "What an unattractive person La Sand is. Is she really a woman." As early as 1837, Maria Wodzińska's mother had made it clear to Chopin in correspondence that the marriage with her daughter was unlikely to proceed. It is believed that she was influenced by his poor health and possibly also by rumors about him having affairs with men and women like Sand. Chopin eventually placed the letters from Maria and her mother in a package on which he wrote, in Polish, "My Tragedy". Sand, in a letter to Grzymała of June 1838, acknowledged strong feelings for the composer and argued for leaving the current relationship to begin an affair with Chopin; he asked Grzymała to assess Chopin's relationship with Maria Wodzińska. Without realizing that the matter, at least from Maria's side, was over.

context_en: Different fields of science use term substances in different, and sometimes inconsistent, ways. Thus, the term "matter" has no universally agreed scientific meaning. Scientifically, the term "mass" is well defined, but "matter" is not. Sometimes "matter" in the field of physics is simply equated with particles that exhibit rest mass (i). , which cannot travel at the speed of light), such as quarks and leptons. context_en: Several molecular mechanisms of antibacterial resistance exist. Intrinsic antibacterial resistance may be part of the genetic makeup of bacterial strains. For example, an antibiotic target may be absent from the bacterial genome. Acquired resistance results from a mutation in the bacterial chromosome or the acquisition of extra chromosomal DNA. Antibacterial-producing bacteria have evolved resistance mechanisms that have been shown to be similar, and have been transferred to antibacterial-resistant strains. The spread of antibacterial resistance often occurs through vertical transmission of mutations during evolution and by genetic recombination of DNA by horizontal genetic exchange. For example, antibacterial resistance genes can be exchanged through these resistance genes between different bacterial strains or species. Plasmids that carry several different resistance genes can confer multiple antibacterial resistance. Cross-resistance to multiple antibacterials can also occur when a resistance mechanism encoded by a single gene confers resistance to more than one antibacterial compound.

context_en: In Whitehead's view, then, concepts such as "quality", "matter", and "form" are problematic. These fail to adequately account for change in "classical" concepts, and ignore the active and experiential nature of the world's most basic elements. They are useful abstractions, but not the basic building blocks of the world. What a person is usually conceived of, for example, is philosophically described as a continuum of overlapping events. After all, people change all the time, if only because they are older than the second and have had some more experiences. These occasions of experience are logically distinct, but progressively linked in what Whitehead calls a "society" of events. By assuming that enduring objects are the most real and fundamental things in the universe, materialists mistake the abstract for the concrete (what Whitehead calls the "fallacy of misplaced objects").

context_en: The Homestead Act of 1862 provided free land to settlers who could claim and "prove-up" up to 160 acres (0.65 km) of federal land in the midwestern and western United States. The first claim by a woman was made near Hot Springs Creek by Miss Gwenlian Evans, daughter of Deer Lodge Montana pioneer, Morgan Evans. By 1880, there were farms in much of central and western Montana's valleys, but few on the eastern plains.

context_en: Early paper made from wood pulp contained significant amounts of a variety of aluminum sulphate salts which are quite acidic. The size was added to the paper to aid in shaping, making it somewhat water resistant so that the ink did not "run" or spread uncontrollably. What early papermakers did not realize was that they added generously to cure almost every problem making their product ultimately harmful. The cellulose fibers that make up the paper are hydrolyzed by the acid, and the presence of alum will eventually degrade the fibers until the paper disintegrates in a process that has come to be known as a "slow fire". Documents written on rag paper were much more stable. The use of non-acidic additives to make paper is becoming more prevalent, and the sustainability of these papers is less of an issue.

context_en: Other animals, such as rabbits and rodents, practice coprophagia behavior – eating special feces to re-digest food, especially in the case of ungulates. Instead they extract more nutrition from the grass by giving their food a second pass through the intestine. context_en: The X3.2 subcommittee designed ASCII based on the earlier teleprinter encoding system. Like other character encodings, ASCII specifies a correspondence between digital bit patterns and character symbols (i). graphemes and control characters). It allows digital devices to communicate with each other and to process, store, and communicate character-oriented information such as written language. Before ASCII was developed, encodings in use included 26 alphabetical characters, 10 numeric digits, and 11 to 25 special graphic symbols. To incorporate all of these, and to control the letters compatible with the Comité Internationale Téléphonique et Telegraphique (CCITT), the Interurban Telegraph Alphabet numbers. 2 (ITA2) standard, FieldData, and early EBCDIC, ASCII required more than 64 codes.

context_en: Feynman has been called "the great explainer". He gained a reputation for being very careful when giving explanations to his students and for creating a moral duty to make the subject accessible. His guiding principle was that, if a subject could not be explained in a fresh lecture, it was not yet fully understood. Feynman derived great pleasure from coming up with such "fresh feminine-level" explanations of, for example, the relationship between spin and statistics. What he said was that groups of particles with spin ½ "repel", while groups with integer spin "clump". This was a brilliantly simple way of showing how the Fermi–Dirac statistics and the Bose–Einstein statistics had developed as a result of studying how fermions and bosons behave under a 360-degree rotation. This was also a question that he considered in his more advanced lectures, and to which he demonstrated the solution in the 1986 Dirac Memorial Lecture. In the same lecture, he further explained that antiparticles should exist, because if the particles had only positive energy, they would not be confined to the so-called "light cone".

context_en: Jehovah's Witnesses believe that their religion is a restoration of first century Christianity. The Governing Body does not issue any single, overarching "statement of faith", but prefers to express its doctrinal position in a variety of ways through publications published by the Watch Tower Society. Their publications teach that doctrinal change and refinement result from a process of progressive revelation, in which God gradually reveals His will and purpose, and from the application of reason and study resulting in such knowledge or "new light". , guidance of the Holy Spirit, and direction from Jesus Christ and the angels. The society also teaches that members of the Governing Body are helped by the Holy Spirit to understand "deeper truths", which are then considered by the entire Governing Body before making doctrinal decisions. context_en: The number of attacks by the species has increased at least since the early 1900s. Species are increasingly being displaced by humans (on purpose and accidentally). In some cases invaders are causing drastic changes and damage to their new habitats (e.g.: zebra mussels and emerald ash borer in the Great Lakes region and lion fish along the North American Atlantic coast). Some evidence suggests that invasive species are competitive in their new habitats because they are subject to less pathogen disturbance. Others report evidence that sometimes suggests that species-rich communities harbor many native and exotic species while some say that diverse ecosystems are more resilient and resist invasive plants and animals. Are. An important question is, "Do invasive species cause extinctions." Many studies cite impacts of invasive species on natives, but not extinctions. Invasive species start increasing locally (i). : alpha diversity) diversity, which reduces the turnover of diversity (i. : beta diversity). Overall gamma diversity may be reduced as species become extinct for other reasons, but even some of the most inevitable invaders (E. : Dutch elm disease, emerald ash borer, chestnut blight in North America) have not caused extinction of their host species. Extinction, population decline, and homogenization of regional biodiversity are very common. Human activities often cause invasive species to colonize their habitats, by introducing them for food and other purposes. An ordinary person looks up, sees a colorful shape, and immediately assumes it is a chair. Using the same example, Whitehead explains that a dog "will act immediately on the hypothesis of a chair and thus will have jumped through to use it." Thus symbolic reference is a fusion of pure emotion perceptions on the one hand and On the other side are causal relations, and it is precisely the causal relations that dominate the more basic mentality (as the dog shows), while it is the sense perceptions that point to a higher grade mentality (as the artist shows).

context_en: Other authors have focused on the structural conditions leading to genocide and the psychological and social processes that create a development towards genocide. A history of devaluation of the group that becomes the victim, past violence against the group that becomes the perpetrator due to psychological wounds, authoritarian cultures and political systems, and the inaction of internal and external witnesses (bystanders) who in all likelihood Contributes to violence developing into genocide. Acute conflicts between groups that are unresolved become intractable and violent and can even lead to genocide. The conditions leading to genocide provide guidance for initial prevention, such as humanizing a devalued group, creating ideologies that embrace all groups, and activating bystander responses. context_en: In 1758, the taxonomist Linnaeus published a classification of species in Systema Naturae that included Canis species. Canis is a Latin word meaning dog, and the list includes dog-like carnivores: the domestic dog, wolves, foxes, and jackals. The dog was classified as Canis familiaris, meaning "dog-family" or family dog. On the next page he records the wolf as Canis lupus, meaning "dog-wolf". In 1978, a review aimed at reducing the number of recognized Canis species proposed that "Canis dingo is now generally regarded as a distinct feral domestic dog. Canis familiaris is used for domestic dogs. Although taxonomically it should probably be synonymous with Canis lupus." In 1982, the first edition of Mammal Species of the World listed Canis familiaris under Canis lupus with the comment: "Probably ancestral to the domestic dog. , Canis familiaris has priority over Canis lupus, but both were published together in Linnaeus (1758), and Canis lupus has been used universally for this species", which refers to the wolf as a member of the family. context_en: Perhaps the earliest Whitehead considered flawed metaphysical beliefs was the Cartesian idea that reality is fundamentally composed of bits of matter that exist completely independently of each other, which he called event-based or " was rejected in favor of a "process" ontology in which events are primary and fundamentally dependent on and interdependent. He also argued that while the most basic elements of reality can be perceived by everyone, in fact everything is constituted by our experience of it. He used the term "experience" extensively, so that inanimate processes such as electron collisions are said to reveal some experience. context_en: Antibiotics are tested for any negative effects on humans or other mammals before approval for clinical use, and are generally considered safe and most well tolerated. However, some antibiotics are associated with a range of adverse side effects. Side effects range from mild to very severe depending on the antibiotics used, the microbial organisms targeted, and the individual patient. Side effects may reflect the pharmacologic or toxicological properties of the antibiotic or include hypersensitivity reactions or anaphylaxis. The safety profile of new drugs is often not established even for those with a long history of use. Adverse effects range from fever and nausea to major allergic reactions, including photodermatitis and anaphylaxis. Common side effects include diarrhea, resulting from a disruption in the species composition of the intestinal flora, resulting, for example, in the overgrowth of pathogenic bacteria, such as Clostridium difficile. Antibiotics can also affect the vaginal flora, and may lead to overgrowth of yeast species of the genus Candida in the vulvo-vaginal area. Additional side effects may result from interactions with other drugs, such as increased risk of tendon damage from administration of a quinolone antibiotic with a systemic corticosteroid. Some scientists have speculated that indiscriminate use of antibiotics alters the host microbiota and is linked to chronic disease.
questions_en: What approvals are required for antibiotics?

context_en: In the CFL, if the game is tied at the end of regulation play, each team is given an equal number of chances to break the tie. Then proceed through the series below. If a team scores a touchdown starting in the 2010 season, it is required to attempt a 2-point conversion. The other team then scrimmages the ball on the same 35-yard line and has the same opportunity to score. After the teams have completed their possessions, if one team is ahead, it is declared the winner; otherwise, both teams each get another chance to score, scrimmaging from the other 35-yard line. After this second round, if there is still no winner, the game ends as a tie during the regular season. context_en: The development of new technologies has made it dramatically easier and cheaper to sequence, and the number of complete genome sequences is growing rapidly. Thousands of complete genome sequencing projects include those for rice, mouse, plant Arabidopsis thaliana, puffer fish, and the bacteria E. coli. In December 2013, scientists were the first to sequence the entire genome of Neanderthals, an extinct species of humans. After his failed engagement to Maria Wodzińska from 1837 to 1847 he maintained an often troubled relationship with the French writer George Sand. A brief and unhappy trip to Majorca with Sand in 1838–39 was one of his most productive periods of composition.
